## Code Changes
- Always read and understand existing code before making changes.
- Make the smallest possible change that solves the problem — do not over-engineer.
- Never remove or break existing working code unless explicitly asked.
- Do not modify unrelated logic. Scope changes tightly.
- Do not introduce linting errors or break formatting rules.
- Do not add or remove blank lines, spacing, or indentation unless required.
- Leave NO placeholders or half-finished sections in final output. All code must be complete and functional.
## Code Quality
- Follow SOLID principles and separation of concerns — but don't over-abstract.
- Prefer functional and declarative patterns over classes where reasonable.
- Avoid code duplication — reuse, modularize, compose.
- If you spot redundant, dead, or inefficient code, suggest a cleanup as a separate recommendation (do not silently refactor).
- Always add proper type annotations. Never use `any` unless explicitly permitted.
- Respect existing linter and formatter settings (Prettier, ESLint, Black, etc.).
## UI & Styling
- Default to **dark mode** for all UI.
- Build modern, polished interfaces — avoid plain/unstyled defaults.
- Pay attention to spacing, color hierarchy, and typography.
- Use Tailwind CSS utility-first conventions (or the project's existing style system).
- Ensure responsive layouts. Test for different screen sizes.
- All interactive elements must have hover states, pointer cursors, and visual feedback.
- Follow ARIA and keyboard navigation best practices for accessibility.
## Naming & Structure
- Use clear, descriptive names for variables, functions, and components.
- Components in PascalCase; functions/variables in camelCase; constants in UPPER_SNAKE_CASE.
- Keep files focused — one responsibility per file where possible.
- Keep rules and functions under 500 lines; split when needed.
## Git & Commits
- Use Conventional Commits format: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`.
- Keep commit messages under 60 characters.
## Error Handling
- Fail fast and fail clearly — catch errors early and surface them explicitly.
- Always log errors with meaningful context. Never silently swallow exceptions.
- Use typed error handling where the language supports it.
